content_chunks.content: The course equips students with the interdisciplinary knowledge and skills to design, implement, and manage a human-centered cognitive buildings that prioritize occupant well-being, sustainability, and innovation. Topics cover fundamentals of human needs, health, and wellness in buildings, using advanced technologies. International case studies provide insights into diverse design strategies, while modules on sustainability highlight the benefits of resource efficiency and productivity improvements in workplaces. The risks and challenges of human-centered buildings, including cybersecurity, costs, and user acceptance are analysed. Other topics include ethical and privacy concerns and project management perspectives. Future trends such as AI, digital twins, and adaptive systems are explored.

Human-centered cognitive building technology for enhanced well-being and workplace productivity - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in designing intelligent buildings that adapt to human needs while optimizing resource efficiency and sustainability. Students master AI-driven building systems, digital twin integration, and adaptive infrastructure that responds to occupant behavior patterns and wellness requirements. The curriculum covers cybersecurity protocols, user acceptance strategies, building evaluation methodologies, and ethical frameworks for privacy-conscious smart environments. Graduates emerge skilled in implementing cognitive building technologies that enhance workplace productivity, reduce environmental impact, and create healthier indoor environments while addressing the complex challenges of user adoption and system integration in modern architecture.
